Shader-Based Renewable Energy Farm Visualization
=================================================

Author: Gunabhiram Aruru
Course: CSCI 4229/5229 Computer Graphics

Project Description
-------------------

This project is an interactive renewable-energy farm visualization written in
C++ using compatibility-profile OpenGL and GLUT. The scene combines wind
turbines, solar panels, energy storage, a Control Center, a greenhouse,
electrical infrastructure, a weather station, livestock, vegetation, terrain,
and other farm details. The models are constructed from handmade OpenGL
geometry rather than imported 3D models.

Original Contribution
---------------------

The main project-specific contribution is a shader-based visualization of wind
flow using animated translucent ribbons. A shared `windSpeed` value controls:

- turbine blade rotation speed;
- wind-ribbon travel, frequency, and displacement;
- the weather-station anemometer; and
- the windsock's lift, extension, and flutter.

The project also provides dedicated inspection modes for major handmade
objects. Each inspection mode reuses the scene model and presents it over a
neutral grid with an individually tuned camera view.

The project began with my Homework 3 foundation, but the final scene expands
substantially beyond that assignment through new handmade geometry, a larger
farm layout, additional energy and farm objects, shader animation, object
inspection, transparency, fog, materials, textures, and optional shadows.

Build and Run
-------------

From the project directory, run:

    make clean
    make
    ./final

Keep `wind.vert`, `wind.frag`, and the `textures` directory beside the
executable because they are loaded with relative paths at runtime.

The Makefile links the OpenGL and GLUT frameworks on macOS. On Linux, it links
GLUT, GLU, OpenGL, and libm; GLEW can be enabled with `make USEGLEW=1`.

Controls
--------

Object inspection:

    0                 Return to the complete farm
    1                 Inspect a wind turbine
    2                 Inspect the Control Center
    3                 Inspect the greenhouse
    4                 Inspect a solar panel
    5                 Inspect the battery / inverter unit
    6                 Inspect a sheep
    7                 Inspect the maintenance worker
    8                 Inspect the boulder cluster

Camera:

    m or M            Cycle orbit, first-person, and overhead modes
    Arrow keys        Rotate orbit view or look in first-person mode
    W / S             Move forward / backward in first-person mode
    A / D             Strafe left / right in first-person mode
    Page Up/Down      Zoom in / out in orbit mode
    + or =            Zoom in in orbit mode
    - or _            Zoom out in orbit mode
    Left mouse drag   Rotate orbit view or look in first-person mode
    Mouse wheel       Zoom in / out in orbit mode
    R                 Reset the full-scene camera and light position

Wind and animation:

    [ / ]             Decrease / increase wind speed from 0.0 to 5.0
    r                 Pause / resume turbine blade animation
    v or V            Toggle wind-flow ribbons
    p or P            Toggle the GLSL wind shader / CPU fallback
    Space             Pause / resume automatic sun movement

Lighting and rendering:

    , / .             Move the sun angle backward / forward
    < / >             Lower / raise the sun
    l or L            Toggle lighting
    t or T            Toggle textures
    g or G            Toggle greenhouse glass
    f or F            Toggle linear distance fog
    h or H            Toggle projected ground shadows
    a or A            Toggle axes outside first-person mode
                      (A strafes left in first-person mode)

Program:

    q, Q, or ESC      Exit

The overhead mode is a fixed orthographic overview. Orbit zoom controls do not
change the overhead or first-person cameras. First-person movement is limited
to the farm boundary.

Professor-Feedback Response
---------------------------

The Control Center entrance and windows were rebuilt to provide clearer depth,
framing, and visual detail. The entrance now has an inset textured door,
panels, a metal frame and handle, a canopy, a landing, and wall lights. Front
and side windows now include dark backing, glass-colored panes, perimeter
frames, and mullions.

These door and window surfaces are close to the building walls. The
implementation applies `glPolygonOffset` only while drawing those facade
overlays, preventing z-fighting without affecting the rest of the scene.

Implemented Features
--------------------

- Handmade scene geometry with no imported 3D models.
- Three animated wind turbines and six shader-driven wind ribbons.
- Textured terrain, roads, buildings, metal equipment, fences, trees, and
  boulders using nine BMP textures.
- Solar arrays, battery/inverter storage, a substation, power poles and lines,
  a greenhouse, a weather station, a windsock, crop rows, sheep, a worker, and
  an Energy Status Display.
- Positional lighting, surface normals, and object-specific material response.
- Transparent greenhouse glass and wind ribbons using alpha blending, depth
  testing, and disabled depth writes during transparent passes.
- Optional linear distance fog, disabled at startup.
- GLSL 1.20 vertex and fragment shaders for wind-flow animation.
- CPU-animated fixed-pipeline wind-ribbon fallback when the shader is disabled
  or cannot compile or link.
- Orbit, first-person, fixed overhead, and eight object-inspection views.
- Optional stencil-masked planar shadows for turbines, the Control Center,
  greenhouse frame, solar panels, sheep, and the maintenance worker.
- HUD status for camera/inspection mode, wind speed, shader/fallback state,
  ribbons, fog, and shadows.

Reuse, References, and AI Disclosure
------------------------------------

This project reuses my previous assignment foundation, including portions of
the camera, projection, GLUT setup, and general scene structure. Course
examples were referenced for OpenGL patterns including texture loading,
lighting, shader setup, and planar projection techniques.

AI tools were used for planning, debugging support, review checklists, README
wording, refactoring suggestions, and small code-pattern suggestions. I
reviewed and integrated the final code and personally tested the completed
program.

Time Spent
----------

Approximately 53 hours total: about 47 hours through the review build and
about 6 additional hours for final implementation, testing, and polish.

Known Limitations
-----------------

- Transparent surfaces are drawn in separate late passes, but individual
  transparent polygons are not depth-sorted.
- Planar shadows are simplified silhouettes projected onto the flat `y = 0`
  terrain. They do not follow raised surfaces, self-shadow, or use soft edges.
- First-person movement is bounded to the farm area but has no collision
  detection against scene objects.
- Wind ribbons appear only in the full-scene and turbine-inspection views.
- Energy Status Display values are illustrative normalized values, not
  calibrated power, weather, or battery measurements.
